		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="Moss-covered Vine maples in the Hoh River Rainforest" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-unmapped-wetlands-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Forested wetlands store vast amounts of carbon, and scientists are trying to quantify just how much. Photo by Nature Picture Library/Alamy Stock Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Forested Wetlands Are Missing from Maps</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Before they can be conserved, “cryptic” carbon-rich wetlands in the Pacific Northwest need to be documented.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by Natalia Mesa 								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						May 31, 2024 | 1,100 words, about 5 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
